<DOC><DOCNO>  ZF107-948-452  </DOCNO><DOCID>07 948 452.andO;</DOCID><JOURNAL>Electronic Engineering Times  Dec 4 1989 n567 p1(2).andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>SIA: U.S.-Japan playing nicer. (Semiconductor IndustryAssociation)</TITLE><AUTHOR>Lammers, David; Robinson, Brian.andM;</AUTHOR><TEXT><ABSTRACT>The Semiconductor Industry Association (SIA) has submitted areport to President Bush that notes evidence of increasedcooperation between US and Japanese firms.andP;  Much of the current'open door' attitude is due to intervention on the part of theJapanese government, which has pressured firms to interact with USsuppliers.andP;  SIA officials warn that US penetration of the Japanesemarket remains limited despite significant recent improvement.andO;The SIA continues to demand that the Japanese honor an allegedguarantee that foreign producers would hold 20 percent of Japan'schip market by 1991; the current share is 11 percent.andP;  ItsJapanese counterpart, the Electronics Industry Association ofJapan, claims greater progress toward the 20 percent goal andaccuses American firms of lackluster marketing efforts.andP;  USindustry officials say that few US firms are willing to take onJapan's special needs.andM;</ABSTRACT></TEXT><DESCRIPT>Topic:     Semiconductor Industry AssociationJapanese CompetitionInternational TradeSemiconductor IndustryIntegrated CircuitsMarket Share.andO;Feature:   illustrationgraphphotograph.andO;Caption:   A bigger IC slice? (graph)andM;</DESCRIPT></DOC>